Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law introducing administrative liability for violation of the term and procedure for payment for goods (works, services) when making purchases for state and municipal needs.
This law is intended to solve a very acute problem of non-fulfillment of their obligations by customers in the implementation of state and municipal purchases.
Two years ago, the situation when entrepreneurs could not receive payment for already executed state and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the General Prosecutor&#39;s Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who entered into contracts not backed by funding, tried in every possible way to evade their payment obligations and included illegal conditions in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the whole country.
Since 2015, in the interests of protecting the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment for public orders, the prosecutor&#39;s office has submitted 9.7 thousand submissions, as a result of their consideration, 4.5 thousand officials were brought to disciplinary responsibility, 533 officials were brought to administrative responsibility, and to investigative bodies to organize procedural 75 materials were submitted, 46 of which were criminalized.
As a result, over 66 billion rubles in debt to entrepreneurs was paid off.
Moreover, these huge sums did not accumulate as a result of non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in paying for services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts led to fabulous debts.
Here is a typical case.
The head of a small company won a tender for the provision of social transportation services for several million rubles.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the due money on time.
The result is a growing financial lump of debts on salaries, taxes, loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not turned to the prosecutor&#39;s office for help.
Now, in a number of regions, the problem has been minimized as much as possible.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts revealed by the prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical values, the prosecutor&#39;s office operates in a manual anti-crisis management mode.
The Prosecutor General personally conducts field meetings with representatives of local authorities, at which all violations revealed by prosecutors and measures for their immediate elimination are examined in detail.
Such operational meetings have already taken place this year in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of Federal Law No. 189-FZ &quot;On Amendments to the Code of Administrative Offenses of the Russian Federation regarding the establishment of administrative liability of the customer&#39;s officials for violation of the term and procedure for payment for goods (works, services) when making purchases to ensure state and municipal needs &quot;, which was signed by the President of Russia last week.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Prosecutor General&#39;s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offenses with an article that provides for a fine from 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by an official of the customer of the term and procedure for payment for goods, works and services in state and municipal purchases.
And if an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offense, then he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already received instructions to ensure the application of these legislative innovations in practice.
