Lazarus - and her friends who fought to put her words on the base of the statue after her death - knew very well that they were committing a completely political act.
The sculpture was intended to indicate the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female image of Liberty.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in her poem the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she received a completely different name: Mother of the Exiled.
The combination of poem and image was a brilliant feminist move and a devastating attack against American nativism.
And how Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the rightists though change it back.
The loud-mouthed Rush Limbaugh, a kind of John the Baptist who heralded Trump&#39;s arrival, argued in 2010 that Freedom invites no one, rather it is an early neocon who carries America&#39;s flame to a world in darkness: “Freedom is moving forward.
