Blocking Critics on Facebook: Don&#39;t run for public office unless you&#39;re willing to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press was.
Americans loved George Washington, but that did not stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism irritated him, of course.
But he didn&#39;t shut up his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said: &quot;You can take away the freedom of speech and we, deaf and dumb, will be led like sheep to the slaughter.&quot;
Now I will turn to the Governor of Maryland, Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan&#39;s subordinates blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And this week the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor&#39;s subordinates called the lawsuit null and void, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of &quot;so what.&quot;
&quot;It&#39;s just Facebook,&quot; many will say.
But this is also important.
And that&#39;s especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a remarkably popular Republican governor in a predominantly democratic state.
He is in second place in the approval rating of the country&#39;s 50 governors.
Hogan is not a die-hard reactionary.
He has demonstrated a strong hand in managing the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also cleverly uses Facebook as his primary means of connecting with his constituents and jokingly displays his bald head after chemotherapy on his page.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor&#39;s page - which is declared as an official public forum and is run by administration officials with taxpayer money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with The Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Chas defended the governor&#39;s actions, arguing that blocking comments was simply moderating them.
But it’s too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters who are malicious on the Internet.
The Post spoke to some of the real people Hogan blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor, who turn to their elected leaders.
They all say their comments were respectful, meaningful, and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to the fact that Hogan is a Catholic.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramana from Bowie, Maryland did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
&quot;I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed at his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news,&quot; she wrote in the comments section of the Post article.
&quot;I also don&#39;t like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it&#39;s so-called cheating, instead of admitting that they are dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens.&quot;
What the governor&#39;s subordinates call a &quot;concentrated spam attack&quot;, others would probably call &quot;an active lifestyle.&quot;
In the era of Facebook, it&#39;s easy to tweak your image by simply blocking out critics or erasing negative comments.
It is a much less dusty job than before, which required sending people out, collecting and burning newspapers with critical editorials, or arresting and gagging protesters.
But this is exactly what is happening now, only in numbers.
Haugen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social media.
President Trump was sued by Twitter users who were banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first landmark decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to the US District Judge from Alexandria, James K. Cashheris, the chairman of the Loudon County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from her Facecbook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was filed with claims by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn&#39;t be that hard.
In the days of Washington, the era of affordable postage took about the same upheaval as the Internet today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters severely undermined his authority.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms &quot;Yurikola&quot;, &quot;Valerius&quot;, &quot;Belisarius&quot; and &quot;Porcius&quot; wrote letters to newspapers ridiculing Washington&#39;s decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the George Washington Papers online project, his office was littered with petitions criticizing his stance on the Treaty of Friendship, Trade and Navigation.
But he didn&#39;t try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing with that.
