She rarely even uses a pot.
In her wooden home in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai district in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually simply places a sweet potato, here called a “note,” right in the hearth.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is taken out and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on an earthen floor - she has no furniture - and this is where she does her housework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The lavatory is a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband&#39;s four wives and therefore was not assigned to work in the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many of the men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are also soldiers.
“No one dares to walk around the village after five in the evening,” she says.
This is a rare glimpse into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by publicly raising their hands in front of the occupying forces.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands has quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control over the region, barring foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes an hour and a half flight from Jayapura, the provincial capital, to Nabir, and then a five-hour shake in a rented car.
There is no public transport here.
The city, with a population of about 19,000, consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; corrugated steel roofs painted with rust in a variety of reddish shades.
Few of the Indonesians, let alone journalists, and almost none of the foreigners made it here.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuans Mee Pago worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes as well.
“It was unusual for us to wear these clothes,” Degei says, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
&quot;We used to wear only leaves on our bodies.&quot;
Papua is Indonesia&#39;s poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates are among the worst in Asia.
But it&#39;s also an Indonesian gold land.
The world&#39;s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a highland province about the size of New Jersey and home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined approximately $ 3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua boasts an estimated $ 78 billion in forest reserves.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that the powerful Indonesian military maintains its suffocating presence here.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $ 20 million, including up to $ 150,000 to one officer.
Demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this gold mine and are ruthlessly suppressed.
Since 1969, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by the Indonesian military, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned, according to human rights activists.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the massacres in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the 1970s could be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We will lose everything, a report published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as summary executions, torture - particularly frequent, another report claims, rape and electric shock - and brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because the accidents happen every week,” says Andreas Harsono, who does research in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The nuts tightened as Papua&#39;s resources attracted an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province&#39;s 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese shops, &quot;varungi,&quot; sell fried chicken and a gado-gado mixture of vegetables, served with peanut sauce.
Locals are trying to compete.
“Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables in the traditional market for less than the indigenous people of Papua,” explains Abet You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, because of work.
&quot;Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua - the mother-mother (women) of Papua - have lost their market.&quot;
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokovi, vowed to tackle inequality and human rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua&#39;s 29 districts, including Paniai.
But in Papua, almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel betrayed.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Djokovi, expecting him to fulfill our hopes for justice,” says Yow.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration, Djokovi Paniai experienced tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols around a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle burst out of the darkness.
The frightened children told them to turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebay, one of the soldiers took offense at their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who were drunk chased the children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus Eimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to the nearby government electoral commission building, and the situation escalated the next day.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on the soccer field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed vaita, a dance of the Papuan tribe mee pago: they ran in circles and depicted birdsong.
Some protesters started throwing stones at the police station and military base.
As the situation escalated, the soldiers were ordered by internal radio communication: &quot;If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,&quot; it sounded like an official document seen by TIME magazine, but which was not published in local media.
Eremias Kayame, 56, head of the Kogo Koto district in Enarotali, sensed danger was approaching and called for calm, asking the crowd to go home.
Nobody wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned around, my left wrist was suddenly hit by a bullet,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn&#39;t know who fired, but says that the bullet came from the side of the assembled ranks of soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
Local resident Alfius Jove was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johannes told TIME magazine, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
&quot;I saw that he was dead ... I kissed him.&quot;
General Yotje Mende, Senior Inspector of the Papua Police, told reporters that his officers were only &quot;defending&quot; their base because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” Papua Police Commissioner Pujo Sulistijo said in 2015.
&quot;It&#39;s a matter of life and death.&quot;
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Djokovi delivered an impassioned speech in Jayapura in which he offered condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the historical abuse of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it will never happen again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Viranto said he would set up a non-judicial organization to end historic human rights abuses.
But almost immediately there were excuses.
“Most of the violations happened long ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or early 2000s.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be passed, ”he said.
Viranto then backtracked, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to establish an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, &quot;Everything will be decided through the courts.&quot;
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of &quot;crimes against humanity&quot; in the deaths of more than 1,000 people in a bloody vote for East Timor independence in 1999, said 11 human rights abuses in Papua had already been resolved, including the incident. to Paniai.
The families of the Paniai victims received such statements with grim disbelief.
“Over the past three years, I&#39;ve been asked four times, but there hasn&#39;t been any change at all,” says Johannes.
&quot;I&#39;m tired&quot;.
He says that years later, he still lives in fear.
“I&#39;m scared,” he says.
&quot;I am afraid that the military will arrest me, I am afraid that they will shoot me.&quot;
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the inhabitants of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping to bury four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came for me,” he says.
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot at villagers in Paniai&#39;s neighboring Deyay district.
Clashes between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to help take the unconscious man to the hospital killed one person and injured 17 others, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Dove, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company&#39;s construction site office.
Police said the villagers threw stones at the officers, who responded by firing warning shots.
But locals say a mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) fired into the crowd and killed one person.
“We were in such a panic, we were afraid of retaliation,” Dominggu Badii, 28, who lives near the hospital and saw the hurried delivery of the wounded, told TIME magazine.
&quot;I hid in my house for two days.&quot;
Deyay&#39;s parliament has demanded that the officers involved in the incident be held accountable and the mobile police brigade withdrawn from the region.
Paniyai has always been a sore spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development is causing discontent among the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout the green, central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to defend Papuans&#39; rights by organizing sporadic kidnapping attacks and raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In retaliation, thousands of people in Paniai have been arrested and groundlessly detained by the military in recent years under the pretext of &quot;defending national independence.&quot;
Some never returned.
Among the population of Papua, Paniai is considered a &quot;sad, forgotten place&quot;.
Poverty increases discontent.
The small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
Bread is not available to the same extent.
The people here grow whatever they eat: mainly the note, but also some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women, each of whom can care for four to five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually save most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold at the local market.
Ten tubers of a note cost only Rs 10,000 (75 cents).
Over time, the economic disparity between the indigenous Papuans and the new migrants who arrived in large numbers following the introduction of new flights to Nabire Airport increased.
The few existing vacancies usually go to more educated and wealthy migrants.
Papuans rarely have enough money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
“Young people do not want to stay in the village ... because there is no work or money here,” says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the views of the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of international media remain severe.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudi and Basile Longchamp were deported from Papua for “lack of coordination with relevant organizations” despite being given rare videotaping permits.
According to Felim Kineh, deputy director for Asia at Human Rights Watch, the promises made during the Djokovi campaign to lift restrictions on media in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
“Now foreign journalists trying to report from the breakaway eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua, face new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of media coverage means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely limited to Papua&#39;s immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific states - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands - asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “diverse and widespread violations” in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arramanata Nasir brushed aside the group&#39;s statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that &quot;Indonesia is still a democratic system and has a free press, so it would be difficult to hide evidence of human rights violations.&quot;
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by Dutch Human Rights Ambassador Kiis Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, locals broke the silence, praying “We want freedom,” according to a source who also attended the meeting but wished to remain anonymous.
Indonesia will have new presidential elections in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokovi again.
“Jokovi is a man with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting,” says Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Djokovi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai, in addition to living in the shadow of the threat from a greedy army, are mired in poverty, and their education and healthcare are in a miserable state.
Gobay says that the inhabitants of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote, given for Djokovi, a debt that he must pay.
“They don&#39;t need money, they just want justice,” he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out a final symbolic act of disobedience: they buried the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly opposite the police and military precinct.
Knowing that justice will probably never prevail, they will at least not allow the guilty to forget their crimes.
“They killed a member of our family,” says Jacobus without looking up.
&quot;What else could we do?&quot;
