The day after the 15-state lawsuit, the head of the EPA reversed his decision to postpone the implementation of Obama&#39;s rules designed to reduce emissions of air pollutants and smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by the fact that his agency is now listening more than in previous administrations to the needs of environmental regulators in individual states.
He did not mention the lawsuit filed against his previous position in a federal appellate court.
The controversy revolved around the October 1 deadline for which states must meet 2015 ground-level ozone standards.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would postpone compliance by one year to give his agency more time to study the plan and to avoid &quot;inconsistencies with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth.&quot;
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma&#39;s attorney general before being appointed by President Trump to his current position, has long been known as a consistent opponent of environmental tightening.
