The unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat for Pewitt&#39;s course of returning to old norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA chief had exceeded his mandate in an attempt to delay implementation of the Obama administration&#39;s rule requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and mitigate methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt suggested that, by dramatically changing course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA&#39;s responsibility to work with states in a comprehensive process to ensure that the new standards are enforced in a timely manner.
&quot;Under previous administrations, the EPA has often failed to meet deadlines, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others and discussed timelines during the settlement process,&quot; said Pruitt, who has filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous role.
“We don&#39;t believe in regulation through litigation and we take the deadline seriously.
We also take seriously our charter and the power it gives us. &quot;
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt may at some point re-use his “deferral and other statutory powers” to ensure that the “jcyjdfys” regulations are on a clear course and on all available information.
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader revision of ozone regulations.
