Clubs have the right to spend large sums of money to acquire players, but they have to balance them with legitimate sources of income in order to reach the threshold of profitability in their football business.
FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his 2007 election as UEFA President.
The former French footballer believed that clubs that went into huge debt in their pursuit of success were, in essence, cheating and risking ruin if banks or owners cut off funding.
In 2011, FFP stopped focusing on club debt and instead switched to tracking club losses.
As a result of this change, the business model that Roman Abramovich originally used in Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with good potential and then invest heavily in order to improve the team and build a global brand - has become an elusive plan.
During the current three-year valuation period, spanning 2018, clubs could suffer losses of € 30 million.
And while Platini was dismissed in disgrace from the presidency in 2015, his successor at UEFA, Aleksandr Čeferin, is still determined to contain excessive spending.
“Of course FFP is alive and we will tighten the rules as we move forward,” Andrea Traverso, who controls FFP at UEFA, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG will pay the ransom of Neymar&#39;s contract at a time, he can distribute this amount for reporting throughout the entire term of his contract.
