Past sanctions against PSG mean that UEFA will be even more closely monitoring any attempts to circumvent the rules.
According to those familiar with the situation on Thursday, UEFA had no preliminary discussions with PSG regarding the transfer of Neymar.
They spoke to the Associated Press on condition of anonymity, as they were not authorized to discuss PSG&#39;s position.
According to the latest published financial statements, PSG generated more than 10 million euros in profit in 2015-16 on a turnover of 542.4 million euros.
The accounts for the last fiscal year have not yet been published.
PSG expects Neymar&#39;s arrival to be fertile ground for sponsorship deals, merchandise and team logo shirts.
The club expects turnover to grow by at least 30 percent as a result of the hiring of a new player.
Undoubtedly angry that one of the best footballers was leaving, the Spanish league tried to thwart Neymar&#39;s transfer, claiming PSG would disrupt financial fair play.
&quot;This is an obvious case of &#39;financial doping&#39;, with the club and the state,&quot; La Liga President Javier Tebas told the Spanish newspaper AS, referring to Qatar as the ultimate owner of PSG.
Arsenal coach Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by the American sports tycoon, shares La Liga&#39;s concerns about state funding for the club.
“These are all equity ramifications and have completely changed the football landscape over the past fifteen years,” Wenger said Thursday.
“When a club belongs to a country, anything is possible.
It becomes very difficult to comply with financial fair play because a country can have many paths and many reasons to be represented by such a serious player.
The order and place of taking the oath will be determined by the President
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the president - such amendments for the second reading to the relevant law were developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Construction.
A week ago, the deputies planned to directly determine the procedure for taking the oath in law.
Children under 18, as well as those incapacitated, will be exempted from taking a solemn oath, according to the revised text of amendments to the bill &quot;On Russian Citizenship&quot; (available to Izvestia), which the committee will consider on July 11 before the second reading at its meeting.
On June 6, President Vladimir Putin supported the idea of introducing an oath when entering Russian citizenship instead of the formal signing of documents during a meeting with State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies formalized this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of a bill providing for the cancellation of the decision to grant citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public calls for terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet ( Part 2 of Art. 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for hijacking an airplane, train or water transport, but only if this act is related to terrorism (Part 4 of Art. 211 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
According to the bill, its logic was as follows: when drawing up documents for citizenship, a person subscribes to a promise to abide by Russian law - having embarked on the path of extremism, he breaks this promise.
The bill was submitted to the State Duma in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasiliev (United Russia), Gennady Zyuganov (Communist Party of the Russian Federation), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov (Fair Russia) and State Duma speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the State Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been revised again.
Now it says that the procedure for taking the oath will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law &quot;On citizenship of the Russian Federation&quot;, indicating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state emblem and flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, from the text of the bill it was not clear where such an event should take place - the list of places where the emblem of the Russian Federation could be placed is regulated by the corresponding federal constitutional law.
These include courts, offices of heads of state power bodies of subjects, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could be registry offices.
Those wishing to obtain Russian citizenship will take the solemn oath after officials check their documents.
But a person will receive a Russian passport only after taking the oath, it follows from the revised text.
A week ago, the draft said that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text states that they will swear allegiance to Russia from the age of 18, and not from 14.
A rule has been preserved according to which incapacitated or partially incapacitated persons, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or personally sign the text of the oath, will be exempted from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt from this procedure and &quot;other persons&quot;
Also, the updated bill spelled out a special procedure for admitting to Russian citizens residents of Ukraine who are considered native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce their Ukrainian citizenship by submitting a corresponding application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
Renunciation of &quot;someone else&#39;s&quot; citizenship, as now, will not be required if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is impossible &quot;for reasons beyond the control of the person.&quot;
A corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, including the first vice-speaker of the State Duma Ivan Melnikov (Communist Party of the Russian Federation), Natalya Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Airat Farrakhov (all - &quot;United Russia&quot;).
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, simply impossible.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for a decision on their fate regarding the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained Pavel Krasheninnikov (ER), the head of the Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation the day before.
In addition, a clarification appeared in the text that restrictions on the occupation of certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who renounced their &quot;other&quot; citizenship in writing and handed over their previous passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but &quot;for reasons beyond his control&quot; did not stop it. be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are prohibited from holding positions in the municipal service, being hired at facilities and organizations whose activities are related to ensuring the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit of another country cannot become a State Duma deputy or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should come into force on September 1, 2017, by that time the necessary by-laws should be ready.
Nostalgia becomes niche in Hot American Summer and Fellow Detective
The current iteration of the story is nostalgically reminiscent at the same time of the glorious days of the characters in the 80s; about the grunge era in the 90s (around the time the great masters David Wayne and Michael Shoalter made the sketch comedy &quot;The State&quot; for MTV); and about herself - that is, 2001, before her stars like Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler and Paul Rudd got down to serious stuff.
As a fact of culture, it is both the rise and embodiment of our era with its constant reminders from Facebook.
But as a franchise, it seems like an anachronism.
Camp One was surprisingly good, and not only because of its absurd humor (including the original story of a talking can of vegetables, voiced by H. John Benjamin).
The result is doubled by the main joke: middle-aged actors play sex-preoccupied children who have just come of age; thanks to this, the inability to return to becomes part of the joke.
Ten Years Later, where the adults played as adults, has less deep emotional roots, and its parody is more haphazard and includes riffs from stalker films from the 90s like The Hand That Rocks the Cradle.
In one episode, a character pulls out an Apple Powerbook, four-wheeled rollerblades, and &quot;a bunch of other things from 1991.&quot;
Many of the plot moves are the same.
Good-natured Coop (Showalter), now a writer, still hasn&#39;t gotten the reciprocity from Katy (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) still has his virginity.
And then there is the insane and dastardly conspiracy involving Ronald Reagan (also Showalter), who is now incited by George W. Bush (a tried-and-true parody played by Michael Ian Blake).
As always, the best part of the franchise is the departures from it.
It’s especially fun to see the forever young Rudd humming a song from Matt Dillon from Loners, whose character, former big man Andy, now looks like an old man.
The franchise could be a success with occasional frenzies like the recursive series &quot;Seven Up&quot; until it gets to what I think would be its logical conclusion: &quot;Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later&quot;, where in the last on stage, the whole company would go to the cinema for the premiere of the movie &quot;Hot American Summer&quot;.
&quot;Comrade Detective&quot; on Amazon refers to a different type of nostalgia: the Cold War memories from &quot;The Americans,&quot; &quot;Explosive Blonde,&quot; or even &quot;Shine,&quot; with its imagery of East-West struggles.
Created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka and directed by Reese Thomas, this comedy depicts a TV movie: an 80s Romanian police drama about two policemen in Bucharest fighting for truth, atheism and the Marxist-Leninist path.
Florin Piercik Jr. and Corneliu Ulich play the main roles - who has seen the life of Gregor and the idealist Joseph - and their dialogues in English are voiced by Channing Tatum (aka executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levit.
This is a brilliant idea.
But just an idea.
There are some visual jokes (the cops spend their time watching a chess match, the way Americans might watch football).
A team of famous voice-overs - among them Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloe Sevigny - allows you to play the game &quot;guess the voice&quot; in an interesting way.
But &quot;Comrade Detective&quot; so clings to the plausibility of a clumsy propaganda drama - there is even a killer in a Ronald Reagan mask - that it often looks like it.
Six long episodes are drawn out, and it’s not very funny, and not often.
If it were made shorter, &quot;Comrade Detective&quot; could better cope with his satire in the spirit of agitprop; for example, every time Gregor and Joseph arrive at the American Embassy, two fat people are sitting in the lobby, eating a bunch of hamburgers.
To the imaginary communist viewer, this image tells that Western culture is capable of making gobble out of anything.
The fictional Romanian filmmakers are not so wrong: We do this even with our own recent history, and with theirs too.
