State health service to prescribe controversial HIV drug for 10,000 people
Beginning in September, patients will have access to a &quot;revolutionary&quot; HIV drug following the battle in the High Court over the funding of the drug from the National Health Service.
The National Health Service of England announced that HIV pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in those at risk by an average of 86 percent, will now be provided by the health service for an initial three-year probationary period of approximately 10,000 people.
She agreed to fund the trial after an appellate court upheld a High Court ruling last year arguing that the NHS has the option to pay for PrEP, despite claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, announced Thursday, has been called &quot;a major innovation&quot; by NHS President Simon Stevens, while the National AIDS Control (NAT) has called it a &quot;turning point.&quot;
Ahead of the full launch of the program across England by April 2018, venereal disease dispensaries in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to register people, with more dispensaries joining the program in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV medications taken before sex to reduce the risk of contracting HIV.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When you take PrEP before sex, you have enough certain drugs in your body to prevent HIV infection.
These drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Eligible patients include homosexual and bisexual men, transgender people, and people whose partners are HIV positive and do not receive successful treatment.
Dispensaries will select eligible study participants, including men, women, transgender people, and people whose partners are not known if their HIV status is being constrained by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and assigned to a general practitioner in England will also be able to apply for potential participation at the nearest participating venereal dispensary.
The program will cost £ 10m and NHS signed a supply agreement this week following an international procurement tender.
The study is designed in such a way as to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical data on who the target audience of the drug is, on its absorption and use on a large scale.
“This critical innovation should complement and reinforce widespread and increasingly successful HIV prevention efforts.
This marks another milestone in more than three decades of success in the fight against one of the largest health threats facing humankind.
Deborah Gold, President of NAT (National AIDS Control Agency), said: “This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, when intelligently targeted at people in need and at risk, provides an opportunity to make a difference in England&#39;s HIV epidemic.
Beginning in September, people at risk of HIV, thanks to this NHS-funded study in England, will have access to a new and exciting tool that the individual can control without discussing it with a partner, resulting in to improve many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news. &quot;
Ian Greene, President of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: “The first priority now is to ensure that the trial rolls out quickly across the country so that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
Now that we are provided with the experimental drug PrEP, we are moving towards protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV. ”
Shadow Public Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: &quot;We very much welcome the initiation of the PrEP trial, it is very late due to months of delays and delays by the government.&quot;
The data demonstrates how revolutionary this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the transmission of this fatal infection.
This test will take us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the trial be rolled out across the country as soon as possible to protect those at risk for HIV and move us one step further towards stopping the spread of HIV in society.
