Judges are offered to be protected from the chairpersons
The Presidential Human Rights Council (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of court presidents and introduce their election.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential assignment.
The HRC has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian justice system.
The HRC carried out this work on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the president gave after a meeting with council members.
At a meeting with council members on December 8, 2016, they discussed, among other things, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of imprisonment of citizens (see Kommersant of December 9).
As a result of the HRC&#39;s work, 25 proposals were made, which relate to both the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and the identification of judicial errors, and the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin&#39;s human rights defenders is to limit the powers of court chairmen in order to increase the independence of the rest of the judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, then the chairman of the court, in the opinion of the HRC, should submit him for appointment without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the chairman of the right to distribute cases for consideration among judges.
Experts admit that this can be done by a specially written computer program.
The HRC also believes that the chairman is not entitled to &quot;predetermine the results of the qualification attestation of a judge, initiate disciplinary proceedings against him, or make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments.&quot;
At the same time, the presidential council considers it necessary to move to &quot;the election of the chairpersons of the courts by the judges themselves&quot; and &quot;empower them for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation.&quot;
Now all the chairpersons of the courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president on the proposal of the chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRC proposes to organize appeals and cassations in courts of general jurisdiction in a new way.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says that &quot;it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts.&quot;
The experts take as a basis the practice of arbitration courts.
Under them there are &quot;judicial districts&quot; that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but due to this, they guarantee greater independence from regional officials who find it difficult to use &quot;telephone law&quot;.
The HRC proposes to reinforce justices of the peace with people&#39;s assessors, so that with their participation some &quot;categories of civil and administrative cases&quot; should be considered.
For example, on the deprivation of parental rights, on reinstatement at work, on the protection of honor and dignity, on the deprivation of a driver&#39;s license, etc.
“These are just our proposals,” Tamara Morshchakova, a member of the HRC, a retired judge of the Constitutional Court, explained to Kommersant.
She also recalled that the President&#39;s instruction referred not only to the HRC, but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
The Armed Forces (among the co-executors are the Prosecutor General&#39;s Office and the Human Rights Ombudsman in the Russian Federation) still have time to carry out the assignment.
The chairman of the Armed Forces, Vyacheslav Lebedev, must report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation before September 1.
Living a tall life: a mezzanine floor and clever design tricks turned this small apartment in Earl&#39;s Court into a spacious home
Joan Lee, a retired banker with a passion for renovating real estate, moved from a spacious home in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a pretty typical Queen Anne style house, and the new design is supported by the fact that Joan did not pack her things and move again.
“I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge in a much larger area,” says Joan.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earl&#39;s Court, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and bid her the same day. &quot;
Since its first viewing, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete refurbishment.
It was originally a one-bedroom apartment with an intricate layout - you had to walk through the kitchen to get to the bedroom - and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a mezzanine to make the most of the generous ceiling heights.
“I wanted high ceilings, large windows, lots of light.
Those were my requirements, ”she says.
To that end, she hired Erfan Azadi of Notting Hill-based architecture and design studio Duck &amp; Shed to use the 12.5-foot ceilings and create a home that would not only be a successful project, but would be suitable for Joan. life.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate the two rooms one on top of the other, so the architectural challenge was to create a mezzanine floor that could stand upright.
Erfan had to be creative to handle the brief.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We needed to arrange the rooms so that they were one above the other, and we didn&#39;t have to bend.
It was necessary not only to build a simple platform, but also to bend the structures so that they were at the correct height and allow the use of the premises from above and below ”.
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-sized rooms one above the other in the allotted space - and much more.
From the mezzanine level, a vintage copper skylight window from Retrouvius overlooks the plush living room below.
Gold-tone mirrored furniture, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures by Serge Muy set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding entertainment, space and light.
The short corridor is framed with mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the mirrored protective panel appears to be a window to another room.
At the entrance, mirrored cabinets hold all of Joan&#39;s crockery.
To create the feeling of a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can obscure the kitchen when not in use.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding door, like in a garage.
“The art of engineering was involved,” says Erfan of the steel-reinforced wood-fiber panel door.
&quot;It&#39;s equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.&quot;
Through clever use of space and storage, Joan received an additional 16 square feet, an extra bedroom and an improved layout.
“At the end of the day, floor space is exactly what you will be selling — that is, what your property is valued at,” says Erfan.
&quot;Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and calculate based on floor area.&quot;
Here they have been able to enlarge the floor area by using quality materials that give the space a touch of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection with home,” says Erfan.
“Nobody falls in love with electrical wiring in the walls.
It is important, but it does not touch the strings of our hearts. &quot;
This is evidence that due to good design and increased footage, an apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can choose to stay.
