We may never know about the tweets that Trump didn&#39;t post.
If his employees saved him from trouble even a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has always been able to keep Trump from adding fuel to the fire.
Part of the problem is that in a White House divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to push their agenda forward by feeding Trump material - reliable or not - that confirms their views.
Politiko - just in time for this story - wrote in May about the propensity of advisers to constantly slip dubious information on the president.
Here&#39;s one example, as described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
“Current and former Trump employees say Trump can react very harshly to negative press coverage, especially those containing dangerous information leaks, and will not rest until he finds who was behind them.
This happened in late February, when someone slipped the president a printout of an article from GotNews.com, the site of the Internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, in which deputy chief of staff Katie Welch was accused of being &quot;behind a series of leaks&quot; in the White House. ...
It doesn&#39;t matter that Johnson is forever banned from Twitter for violent behavior, that he did not provide specific facts, or that he has launched false accusations and then dropped them in the past.
Trump read the article and started asking employees about Welch. &quot;
Goldmacher adds that then-chief of staff, Raines Priebus, and secretary of the staff, Rob Porter, &quot;were trying to build a system to manage and document the flow of papers Trump receives.&quot;
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly tries to do the same.
He may turn out to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump still has an impulsive nature, and his aides continue to fight each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly&#39;s task very difficult.
Tyumen Prosecutor&#39;s Office Fights HIV Dissident
The prosecutor&#39;s office challenged the ruling of the Kalininsky District Court of Tyumen, which terminated the criminal case against a local resident, whose young daughter died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died due to the fact that the mother is an HIV-dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court released her from responsibility in connection with the reconciliation with the injured father.
The prosecutor&#39;s office believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished so as not to create a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against a resident of Tyumen was initiated under Part 1 of Art. 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (causing death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection stage 4B.
According to the prosecutor&#39;s office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
&quot;The woman did not receive treatment herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist,&quot; the Tyumen region prosecutor&#39;s office explained.
The criminal case was submitted to the Kalininsky District Court of Tyumen, which on July 25 made a decision to terminate it.
The petition for this was submitted by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that &quot;he forgave his wife, has no complaints against her, she made amends for the harm and apologized.&quot;
The prosecutor&#39;s office did not agree with the decision of the court and filed an appeal, demanding to cancel the decision to dismiss the case and send it for a new trial.
The girl died, and it is impossible to make amends for the harm caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the doctors&#39; recommendations, refused to examine the baby and treat her for a dangerous infection, ”the press service of the prosecutor’s office said.
According to the supervisory authority, she must be punished, otherwise other HIV dissidents will follow her example.
As told in the Tyumen AIDS Center, now in the Tyumen region about 12 children with HIV do not receive medical care due to the refusal of their parents.
“And this situation has already improved - during the year of the work of the special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat their children for HIV changed their minds - they allowed them to carry out diagnostics, began to take medications,” said Elena Loseva, press secretary of the AIDS Center.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents in a legislative way, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children can be detected - mothers do not allow them to be examined, they hide, and run away from hospitals with their children.
The Dangers of HIV Dissidents
At the end of last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of Russia&#39;s first study of the so-called movement of HIV dissidents.
HIV dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medications.
Doctors and activists of AIDS service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and see their spread as a serious threat.
A terrible photo session, which ended in tragedy, took place on Thursday, August 3, at the Grechany railway station in Khmelnytsky.
