The gypsies overcame the moat and returned to the &quot;street of millionaires&quot;
Some of the wealthiest homeowners in the West Midlands are once again in conflict with determined Roma who have crossed the ditch dug by the municipal government to reoccupy the field next to their homes.
Gypsies have parked 20 mobile homes in a field bordering the wealthy Solihall Street, jokingly dubbed &quot;Millionaire Street.&quot;
Bringing horses, babies and many mobile homes with them, they returned after being kicked out as recently as May, and were not prevented by a moat dug by the municipal government to prevent their incursions.
This tactful company found a gap in the defenses and squeezed their vehicles through an area that had been left open to make room for a path.
Furious residents attacked Solihull municipality, saying it was &quot;unable to solve this problem.&quot;
An anonymous local resident said: &quot;They came here on Monday evening after being driven out of Bentley Heath, where they threw stones at passers-by.&quot;
The municipality should be shamed and forced to act, because they are completely unable to solve this problem.
The gypsies were here in May, they were driven away, and now they are back again.
More Roma came last night, and perhaps more today.
“The municipality of Birmingham knows how to fix this problem, they get long-term court orders to protect their parks,” she added.
I live on Streetsbrook Road and I don’t like the fact that I continue to pay council tax and the municipality cannot even put an end to it. ”
One local resident, who asked to remain anonymous, said: &quot;This is ridiculous, we just saw these gypsies leave the previous time, and here you are, this attack continues.&quot;
This time there were more of them, and we even saw a horse grazing in the meadow. &quot;
A spokesman for the Solihull Municipality said: “We are aware of an illegal camp on the ground near Streetsbrook Road and we are cooperating with the Solihull police; we are taking the necessary legal action to drive them out as soon as possible. &quot;
To help us collect evidence, it is very important that as many local residents as possible report any antisocial or criminal behavior to the police by calling 101.
