Italy is tightening its tone against NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue operating unless they comply with the new rules governing their operations.
&quot;If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say if they will be able to continue their activities,&quot; Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin daily Stampa.
Minniti&#39;s warning came the day after Italian authorities confiscated a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet, on suspicion that its crew was in fact collaborating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which only worked for a year, declined to comment on the merits of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
&quot;For us, saving human life is and will remain a top priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue our activities in the search and rescue zone now,&quot; the organization said in a statement on social networks.
&quot;We will be able to assess all the charges brought forward now, only after we collect all the information and are able to assess the situation.&quot;
Italian authorities have been monitoring Jugend Rettet&#39;s vessel Juventa since October.
Its crew is suspected of taking on board migrants with whole lifeboats, who were sent directly to them by traffickers, and allowing smugglers to leave with boats that they could reuse.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, according to the prosecution materials, the contents of which were published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the instructions of the Italian coastal authorities, which oversee the rescue operations in the area, more out of humanitarian zeal than for any other reason.
The Code of Conduct presupposes, in the main, that vessels of the Juventa type will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to comply with the code: Save the Children, the Maltese MOAS and Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it considers the new rules unnecessary, but acceptable provided they do not cause any &quot;significant change or hindrance&quot; to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign is the Nobel Prize-winning organization, Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said the sharp decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicates that efforts to support the Libyan coast guard and cooperation with local mayors are paying off.
“In recent days, we have begun to see a light at the end of the tunnel,” the minister said.
He announced plans for further talks with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving these countries in hopes of reaching Europe.
&quot;In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict&quot;
The Russian authorities have recently noticeably intensified their policy in the Libyan direction, and delegations of the opposing Libyan parties have become frequent visitors to Moscow.
Lev Dengov, the head of the Russian contact group on intra-Libyan settlement under the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic, told Kommersant what goals Moscow is pursuing in this region and on whom it relies.
Almost nothing is known about the contact group on Libya, which you lead.
For example, the contact group for Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
And here is a veil of secrecy.
What exactly are you doing, what are your goals?
The contact group was created on the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Duma deputy from Chechnya - Kommersant).
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker Mechanic Chebotarev (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - Kommersant).
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group was created from military specialists, representatives of the State Duma, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya, Ramzan Kadyrov.
How did it happen that you were the one to lead it?
Since I have been working in Libya since 2008, I was approached with an offer to lead the work of the group.
Our activity was not limited to the release of seamen from &quot;Mechanic Chebotarev&quot;.
We managed to establish contacts with representatives of all the main groups opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Saraj is based. - Kommersant), and Tobruk (the seat of the parliament, which opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya. - &quot;Kommersant&quot;).
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Libya&#39;s Deputy Prime Minister - Kommersant), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, and dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I want to especially emphasize: in Libya, we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict, we are engaged in a dialogue with everyone.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
The contact group now includes five people.
Among them there are people with experience of work in law enforcement agencies, including the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to include in the group of specialists in the region, representatives of the Institute of the Near East of the RAS.
No one of our employees is permanently in Libya, there is no need for this yet.
Are there Russian military advisers and instructors in Libya now?
And if so, on which side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this do not correspond to reality.
But your contact group includes former military personnel ...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or such cities closed to us until a certain moment as Misurata (where the militia units that played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and became noticeably more active in subsequent years are based. - Kommersant).
We arrived in Misurata in January this year.
We were frightened, they said that everyone there was completely Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there ourselves, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the real role of the Islamists there.
In Misrata, we met with all representatives of the detachments that were engaged in the destruction of IS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the Islamic State banned in Russia - Kommersant).
We wanted to see them, get to know these people, check the information that it was they who played a decisive role in the destruction of IS in Libya, and not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these merits to himself.
And what conclusion did you come to?
Is it not Haftar who defeated the Islamic State in Libya?
It wasn&#39;t he who was doing this.
Haftar was conducting operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And the structures subordinate to the government in Tripoli fought with IS in Sirte.
And, by the way, we invited the people who conducted this anti-terrorist operation to Russia.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from April 19 to April 23 this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, the Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the National Guard.
You, as we understand, have been in all Libyan regions and, probably, can imagine the mood of local elites and warlords.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreement and the holding of elections that Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj reached in Paris at the end of July?
Or again, as has happened many times in the past, will the agreements be thwarted, hostilities will resume, and the parties will try to seize power on their own?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, both leaders spoke extremely negatively about each other.
As for the position of Russia ...
They often write and say that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe in this.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and on that very day Haftar was boarding the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misrata they did not believe in coincidence.
We were told: &quot;You are probably very brave people who came to us today.&quot;
But our task is precisely to show: we do not support only Haftar, we are conducting a dialogue with all the key participants in the conflict in Libya.
You spoke with Haftar.
Does the fact that he studied twice in the USSR make it easier to understand with Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
Even if he knows Russian, it is very relative.
But the fact that he studied with us, of course, facilitates the dialogue with him.
And by the way, not only with him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or else in the Soviet Union.
And now they speak excellent Russian.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent they feel nostalgia for it.
Do you think the imminent lifting of the arms embargo against Libya is likely?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but, as I have already said, we do not take sides in this conflict and would not want to arm some at the expense of others.
We would like everyone to be in approximately equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, the Libyans are constantly calling for Russia to somehow contribute to its lifting.
Now in Libya, the process of drafting a constitution is actively advancing.
We hope that the parties will come to compromise solutions and achieve an internal consensus.
Then elections should take place, which was also discussed at the meeting between Saraj and Haftar.
If the elections take place and a legitimate government is finally elected (and now none of the parties has such a status), then the question of lifting the arms embargo can be raised in the UN Security Council.
Raising this issue is now pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees floating from Libya, feels abandoned to the mercy of fate by its allies from the EU.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is the option that Haftar&#39;s troops would establish control over the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers who smuggle immigrants to Europe?
This is a very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need the support of Russia, because Moscow is engaged in a dialogue with Haftar, and with Saraj, and with Misurata and with the south of the country.
And in this matter, the tribes in the south of Libya play an important role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Are you talking about southerners blocking the flow of migrants at distant approaches?
That is, relatively speaking, did you turn back the buses in which Nigerian migrants travel?
We are trying to achieve this.
But it’s not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help unite the southerners in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But first, we would like to see a consensus on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of the government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia norms in the country.
How radical is he?
Will this not become an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I will express my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, he, on the contrary, is an opponent of radical Islam.
But Islamists are in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself adheres to the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he also actively fights terrorists.
Where did he get such a reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, where the legislative, executive and judicial powers are located.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other government agencies.
Of course, some countries were interested in us not getting in there.
And we mixed all the cards for them and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has entered into a cooperation agreement with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
NOC director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosneft Igor Sechin made a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to the Rosneft company took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I suppose to resell.
And what other economic interests does Russia have in Libya?
There are plans to re-sign the contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
We are talking, in particular, about the previous agreements in the transport sector (construction of railways), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have something to pay with?
Well, they have oil.
That is, it is, as in the case with Iran, about the &quot;oil for services&quot; scheme?
I don’t know what the scheme will be, I don’t deal directly with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are, in fact, engaged in peacekeeping work there.
The main thing for us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans come to an agreement among themselves so that they can establish order in themselves and Libya ceases to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is precisely the main task - to help the Libyan people and squeeze out the terrorists from there.
Do you have information about the presence in Libya (now or earlier) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that today there is not a single native of Russia and other countries of the former USSR there.
He said that he had about 50,000 telephone tapes of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya - Kommersant) and that Russian was not spoken there.
And from what states then are these militants?
I would not like to go into these details.
Then we will formulate the question differently.
How many Libyans are among the Islamist militants in Libya?
There are practically no Libyans among them, there are no more than 5%.
The rest are aliens.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks following the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow and announced their readiness to come again - to Moscow or Grozny.
And when can such negotiations take place?
It&#39;s hard to say now.
Several more visits are to take place, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of the talks.
