A Massachusetts resident was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for encouraging her boyfriend, Konrad Roy, to commit suicide through text messages and phone calls.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will have to serve 15 months of her sentence behind bars and another 5 years on probation.
Carter was convicted in June of the manslaughter of Konrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy&#39;s father said at a hearing on Thursday: “My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend. &quot;
Carter was allowed to remain at large pending an appeal.
She faced a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict while standing, hands clasped and eyes downcast.
“By her actions, she killed Konrad Roy,” the prosecutor told the court.
&quot;She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She didn’t accept responsibility, ”she said.
&quot;She showed no remorse.&quot;
But Carter&#39;s lawyer said it was &quot;a tragic incident that she deeply regrets.&quot;
However, Judge Lawrence Moniz said that in his opinion, her &quot;age, level of maturity or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions.&quot;
The prosecutor read out the statements of Roy&#39;s mother Lynn Roy, which said: “Not a single day has passed when I did not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I cope - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever, &quot;- says it.
Roy&#39;s sister Camdin Roy said she was haunted by the thought that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become an aunt to his children.
&quot;To be deprived of a person who has always been with me since my very birth is a pain that will remain with me until the end of my life,&quot; she said.
This case is likely to become a legal precedent, since there is no law in Massachusetts that would provide for responsibility for advising a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in his car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case caught the attention of the whole country when it became known that it was pushed to commit suicide by Carter&#39;s message.
“You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, I don’t know there are many ways,” she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was vacationing with his family.
A few minutes before committing suicide, she wrote: &quot;You have to do this, Konrad&quot; and &quot;You just need to turn on the ignition, and you will be free and happy.&quot;
Judge Moniz said that Carter wanted attention through Roy&#39;s death and forbade her to speak to the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of lawyers on this matter were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of the murder of her British flatmate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
Knox, 30, published her dissenting opinion in the Los Angeles Times, which stated: &quot;Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not jail.&quot;
