Astronomers have found a &quot;hellish&quot; planet on which even iron can melt
Having first studied the properties of the stratosphere of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, astrophysicists were quite surprised by its temperature, which is able to vaporize iron and other metals.
Experts have noticed that water molecules are so heated by the light of the star that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble Telescope has captured the glow of water molecules on this gas giant: this heat causes the water in the planet&#39;s atmosphere to glow in the infrared.
WASP-121b belongs to the so-called &quot;hot Jupiters&quot; - gas giants comparable in size and mass to the largest planet in the solar system, but located dozens of times closer to the parent star.
Because of this, a year on an exoplanet lasts only 1.3 &quot;Earth&quot; days, and its gas shell is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change threatens lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and Southern France, but now there are fears that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender grows impaired due to dry weather and disease-carrying insects; this has caused constant headaches for scientists and farmers trying to find a solution.
Eric Shes, an expert at CRIEPPAM, an agricultural research institute in Provence, says: “Lavender in Provence is indeed under threat because in recent years this plant has been experiencing the effects of climate change, with much less rain in the spring and especially in the fall.
This affects the lifespan of lavender.
And then there are the little cicadas, leaf-jumping insects that carry micro-bacteria; in very dry weather there are a lot of them. &quot;
There is a lot at stake.
Lavender not only attracts vacationers; lavender oil is in great demand in perfumery and cosmetology.
Eric Shes says: “Instead of very long ears with a large number of large flowers, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened or none at all.
Therefore, we have fewer parts containing essential oil. &quot;
Solutions currently being considered include improving water distribution and slowing soil evaporation, as well as spraying plants with a protective clay and water mixture and developing varieties that are more drought tolerant.
