The murder of a journalist underlines the growing danger in Mexico.
Employees of the weekly newspaper Riodose usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover the latest violent crimes in Sinaloa, involving organized crime, corrupt officials or the ongoing drug war.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about safety.
They were told that they must change their habits.
The two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking the kids with you to an office that had been grenade thrown at in 2009, or leaving them at home.
The security experts wrote three words on a board hanging in the room: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - no proof is needed, suspicion and inner feelings will suffice.
These are drug dealers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being supported by the government or cartels, a whole list of scoundrels who make the work of covering chaos in Mexico dangerous.
Violence gives no respite, and there are more and more journalists among the corpses that are multiplying in the country: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and this year, at least seven people have died in seven states.
Among the latter is their publisher and inspirer, Riodose co-founder Javier Valdes Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,” Valdez wrote in one of his many books on violent drug crimes.
His absence is felt very keenly, although his presence is ubiquitous - a large photograph of Valdez showing his middle finger with the words &quot;Justice&quot; hanging on the facade of the Riodos building; Two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts that show his smile, his glasses face, or his signature Panama hat.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their common trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although the office of a special federal attorney was set up in 2010 to investigate journalistic cases, so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, only two cases have been investigated.
As with most of the thousands of drug and organized crime murders committed each year, journalist killers are rarely brought to justice.
Riodose journalists insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are heartbroken, although the surroundings are now much more dangerous.
Without information about the killers, without justice, talking about security in meetings is of little use, Ibarra says.
“It’s very foolish to waste time in this workshop,” he says.
&quot;Until we know the reason, we suspect everyone.&quot;
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the Riodose office in the state capital, Culiacan.
He managed to drive only a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot at 12 times, probably because of the name of the newspaper - which means &quot;Twelfth River&quot;.
The shooter drove away in his car and crashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He is survived by a wife and two grown children.
Rumors usually spread quickly around Culiacan.
But almost everyone is silent about Valdez.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited in the US last January, Sinaloa has become one of the bloodiest battlegrounds in the country as rival factions fight to fill the void.
Let&#39;s not talk about the fact that every day one or more people are killed on the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with decorated two-story mausoleums of drug queens, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Let&#39;s forget for a moment that the state of &quot;calm&quot; is simply when one of the cartels takes control of a coastal state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Valdez was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bohorquez, 60-year-old co-founder and director of Riodos, is crushed by guilt for failing to protect his friend.
He thinks two mistakes helped the murder.
First, an interview was published in February with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival factions of the cartel, which is at war with the sons of Guzmán.
The publication could anger the sons; people who were allegedly gang members bought up all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper was taken over that was writing about the same story.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
It took him so long to get away from danger, his friends and colleagues thought that he would always be.
He was a seasoned reporter at Noroest and in 2003 he founded Ryodose with five colleagues, selling his $ 50 shares.
In Sinaloa, &quot;it was impossible to do journalism without touching on drugs,&quot; Bohorkes said.
Over time, the newspaper developed a reputation for being bold and honest, and sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists loved that they could publish bold stories without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted by the fact that in this publication they could read about things that no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, Ryodose received the prestigious Maria Moores Cabo Award for reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Prize for his courage to investigate the drug trade in Mexico wherever it takes.
He frankly admitted that he was scared.
“I want to move on,” he said at the CPJ Awards.
The drug trade in Sinaloa is &quot;a way of life,&quot; he said in an interview with Rompevento TV last October.
&quot;You have to accept the tasks that fall on you as a journalist - either that, or you are just playing the fool.&quot;
I don&#39;t want to be asked, &quot;What did you do when there were so many deaths around ... why didn&#39;t you say what was happening?&quot;
The Riodos staff miss Valdez, the joker who swore like a loader in the port, a friend who was generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to survive.
They relied on their routines.
He had to always wear his hat.
He had to go to El Guayabo, the bar opposite the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: was it his love for the once established order ruined him?
His death caused them to question their calculations of how best to do their job and stay alive.
“They don’t like it when you understand their wives, children, their legal business and underground drug airfields.
&quot;These things were over the line,&quot; Bohorkes said.
The result, even in the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from things that smell bad.
The problem, says Riodos editor Andres Villarreal, is that &quot;the sense of smell can be tricked ... and then what happened to Javier happens.&quot;
The old rules, he and others say, are no longer valid in Sinaloa - as in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states, where there is a toxic mixture of lucrative smuggling routes, weak government institutions and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
Cell phones were suddenly forbidden to bring in cell phones into the room where Riodose employees had gathered for a security training: a few days earlier it had become known that spyware, sold exclusively to governments, was being used in Mexico to spy on journalists and civic activists.
Outside, two police officers take refuge in the shade of a tree from the 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were given the task of the state government to guard the office of &quot;Ryodose&quot;, which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois quarter of Culiacan.
Some journalists half-jokingly asked if these police officers were included in the 50 percent of law enforcement officers about whom the governor himself said that they could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists traveled to a mountainous area that is de facto under the control of drug gangs.
In the next issue of &quot;Ryodose&quot; he counted on three main themes.
This is the murder in Sinaloa of the brother of the former boxing champion Julio Cesar Chavez.
They also had exposure of government spending concentrated in the governor&#39;s hometown.
And there was a gang kidnapping in one of the most expensive restaurants in Culiacan, a block from the prosecutor&#39;s office.
It was not officially announced who was kidnapped or how it happened, so it was necessary to be careful when it came time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was the favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and authorities.
One of the journalists learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Revolutionary Institutional Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of government for most of the past century.
Recently, high-profile allegations of corruption have been leveled against several PRI governors.
Villarreal asked reporters to write about previous incidents at the restaurant, including when the son of &quot;El Chapo&quot; Guzmán eluded a military raid.
Just a few months ago, readers would have been looking for Valdez&#39;s column with the most reliable information about the kidnapping.
&quot;Before, we would have known what happened,&quot; says Villarreal, 46, nicknamed &quot;El Flaco&quot; for his lean physique.
&quot;Today all channels of communication with our sources have been severed.&quot;
Valdez&#39;s office is now being used as a warehouse for posters and stickers to protest the murder of journalists, because employees have become what they never thought to be: activists speaking on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took some of the posters and went the next morning to a demonstration outside the local prosecutor&#39;s office about another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the western state of Michoacan three days after Valdez was killed.
A burnt body was found and authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
All over the country, journalists began to speak out louder, organize protests and write &quot;SOS Press&quot; on sidewalks and walls.
Director Bohorquez was in Washington that day, seeking international support for demanding justice in the Valdez case.
In a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after Valdez&#39;s assassination, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their killings for telling the truth.
She then asked not to be given any more government reporting assignments, fearing that her anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdez has said many times that journalists in Mexico are &quot;surrounded&quot; by organized crime, its complicit in government and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Narco Journalism, he wrote that it is not just drug gangs that kill reporters; they do so at the behest of politicians and security forces in cahoots with organized crime.
The Press Protection Committee Artikulo 19 believes that half of the attacks on journalists last year were ordered by police and government officials.
&quot;In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up,&quot; Ramirez says.
Of course, killings terrify people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
A note was found on her body, allegedly written on behalf of the Zetas cartel: &quot;I am here because of my articles.&quot;
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her severed head.
Some publications have opted to close, such as El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua, after its correspondent Miroslava Brich was killed in March.
Others continue to hang on, like &quot;El Magnana&quot; from Nuevo Laredo after the assassination of its boss in 2004.
In 2010, &quot;Diario de Ciudad Juarez&quot; publicly reached out to drug cartels with a front page editorial entitled &quot;What do you want from us?&quot;
Some journalists have left their home states or the country altogether.
This is a painful decision.
It is difficult to find work in exile, and they still look out for danger in the streets.
And sometimes they are killed, as apparently happened to the photographer Ruben Espinoza, who was killed in 2015 with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay and continue to work balance daily between risky decisions.
Ibarra - who once dreamed of being a poet - admits that he is scared to write about the drug trade.
“Mexico is going to hell, and that&#39;s why I became a journalist,” he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, just as the last issue was ready for print, Ryodose&#39;s publishers were sitting on the sidewalk outside their office drinking beer when suddenly their phones rang at the same time.
A series of skirmishes between rival gangs and security forces near the resort town of Mazatlan have left behind what has been confirmed to be 19 corpses.
The war continued to flare up, as promised in a series of messages from cartels found in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they uploaded the news to the Ryodose website via their mobile phone.
The next day, the first page had to be redone.
Sirens sounded nearby — another skirmish in the vicinity.
Bohorkes looked to see if the police guarding them were ready for defense.
If they were scared, they didn&#39;t show it in any way.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was on display throughout Sinaloa, the Riodose staff continued his work.
&quot;How can you think of closing down,&quot; Bohorquez said, &quot;if, on the very day Javier was killed, a trainee asked me to send her outside to report?&quot;
The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit terrifying.
The researchers said that the first remains of an incredible creature the size of a rhino, discovered by a Canadian miner, were so well preserved that experts called it the &quot;Mona Lisa among the dinosaurs.&quot;
It was so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of his scaly skin was reddish brown - and say that he had, in some way, a &quot;dark past.&quot;
In a report published in the journal Contemporary Biology, it was described as &quot;the best-preserved Thyreophorus ever found and one of the finest dinosaur specimens in the world.&quot;
This fossil is a recently found specimen of a nodosaurus that lived in the mid-Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good fortune has stunned researchers who call him &quot;truly wonderful.&quot;
This herbivorous thyreophore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind ever found, according to articles in National Geographic magazine.
It was found by Sean Funk while he was working at Suncor&#39;s Millennium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He stumbled upon something that seemed to be different from the surrounding breed, and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
For the next six years, work was carried out to locate the animal inside a block of earth weighing 2,500 feet (1,100 kilograms).
Now that all this hard work has been done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
“One has to squint a little and you can almost believe he’s asleep,” said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology, which is showing the creation.
&quot;It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved specimens of dinosaurs - the Mona Lisa among the dinosaurs.&quot;
Examining its skin, the researchers found that this herbivore, despite being covered in a shell and resembling a walking tank, appears to be in significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and employed a protective technique known as defensive coloration, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow him to quickly blend in with his surroundings and avoid encountering enemies, experts say, suggesting that he was being hunted by larger dinosaurs.
This 110-million-year-old creature of the Nodosaurus family was highlighted in print in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Scientists have already studied the animal and gave it the name Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of the museum laboratory assistant Mark Mitchell, one of the team members who spent more than 7,000 hours excavating it.
The specimen&#39;s remarkable preservation allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and carapace plates on his body.
They discovered protective coloration, a common defense method in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although protective coloration is well-established, the discovery came as a surprise because the Borealopelta dinosaur is much larger than living animals with protective coloration.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred masking confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with protective coloration - for example, deer, zebras or armadillos - are much smaller and more affordable prey, which indicates that the Nodosaurus had to fight hard to survive.
“The massive predatory threat to the massive, heavily sheltered dinosaur shows how dangerous the carnivorous dinosaurs of the Cretaceous were,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in dinosaur scales also suggests that its skin must have been reddish brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about its life, including the preserved contents of its digestive tract, in order to find out what it ate during its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, he fell into the river and was carried into the sea, where he sank and lay down on the ocean floor with his back.
Back then, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and rivers and oceans likely extended much further inland than they do now.
&quot;This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered in its preserved scaly skin, while at the same time it is completely preserved in three dimensions, retaining the original form of the animal,&quot; said Brown.
“As a result, the animal now looks much the same as it did back then in the Early Cretaceous.
You don&#39;t need to use your imagination too much to recreate it, you just have to squint a little and you can almost believe that he is asleep. &quot;
The Cretaceous Period is the era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of these, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, one of its formidable ancestors may have hunted thyrophores.
These include the Acrocantosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5-meter) monster weighing six tons.
Scientists, whose latest discoveries are published in the journal Contemporary Biology, believe that Borealopelta was carried away to the sea after death and mummified in silt.
The creature was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Millennium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to museum staff, it is the best-preserved thyrophore in the world, complete with skin and carapace, and is intact, from the muzzle to the thighs.
On average, these creatures reached approximately 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3000 pounds (1300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes protruding from the shoulders.
Researchers believe this herbivorous thyreophore tread heavily across what is now Canada until a flooded river swept it out to sea.
But the dinosaur&#39;s underwater burial preserved its shell down to the smallest detail.
The fossils of this particular specimen are so well preserved that remnants of skin still cover the lumpy carapace plates along the dinosaur&#39;s skull.
As Michael Greshko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, this degree of preservation is &quot;as rare as winning the lottery.&quot;
The longer I look at it, the more striking it seems.
The fossilized remains of skin still cover the lumpy armor plates dotting the animal&#39;s skull.
His right front leg is extended along the side, with five toes turned upward.
I can count the scales on his sole. &quot;
