How did one activist know the answer to the question &quot;Whose streets?&quot;
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shocked to the core.
Just a day after arriving in New York on a tourist trip, the St. Louis native was sitting on a bed in an Airbnb rented apartment, browsing her Facebook feed on her phone.
She came across the post of someone from high school.
It said, &quot;The police have just killed an eighteen-year-old child, and he is still lying in the middle of the street.&quot;
Noticing that no one else from her feed posted this information, puzzled, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
In her feed, there were many re-posts of the user with the nickname @TheePharoah.
The Greater St. Louis rapper tweeted in real time the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed eighteen-year-old black young man killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photograph of Brown&#39;s lifeless body, sprawled in the middle of the street, where it will remain for four hours.
This is wildness, Ferrell thought.
But death was not something new for her and her circle.
She put her phone down and later in the evening returned to tweets about people gathering at Canfield Drive.
There were photographs of a signal tape and people screaming and a man claiming to be Brown&#39;s father holding a poster that said, &quot;A Ferguson cop just killed my unarmed son!&quot;
She watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another police officer, she said, pulled the trigger on his rifle and yelled, &quot;I&#39;ll kill you all ... animals!&quot;
&quot;This is a non-standard situation,&quot; - according to her own recollections, Ferrell said then.
“This is not the kind of murder that we are used to and which we can call typical.
At that moment, I felt a chill.
I got angry and cried. &quot;
She took a return flight and flew home the next day.
After landing at 11pm, she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father&#39;s house and decided that they would both go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next nearly three years is the subject of a new documentary, Whose Streets ?, which will be released on 11 August.
It is a story of survival and protest, love and loss, strength and resilience from the perspective of people living in the community and filling the streets, demanding answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a flowered dress and a matching wreath, they recalled the conversation they had had countless times before that morning, &quot;about the experience of blacks and their plight.&quot;
She recalls saying, “Do you remember how I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We&#39;re going to Ferguson now because a policeman killed an eighteen-year-old boy and it was wrong. &quot;
“I couldn&#39;t help but take it,” Ferrell said later.
“What is happening today is the culmination of ... what happened before.
She needs to know about it, see it and be brought up on it.
She must not only be well versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of black experience and situation and what we must do to become free in order to be free.
Even if I manage to provide her with an environment in which she herself does not face obvious racism herself, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would be doing her a disservice if I could keep her out of it. &quot;
When they arrived in Ferguson, they made their first stop at South Florissant Road, a campground across the street from the police station, while activists awaited reports of the final non-prosecution of Officer Darren Wilson.
There, Ferrell and his daughter joined a local entrepreneur preparing lunch bags.
They collected packages and helped distribute them to protesters.
Little by little, a new type of activism took shape in Ferrell&#39;s mind.
“My activism has completely changed since August 9,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri St. Louis, she served as president of the Minority Nursing Students Association and focused on food equity and health inequalities among black communities. ...
“I had no experience as an organizer.
It came by itself. &quot;
A few weeks later, at an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaa Folaian, one of her co-directors.
Folajan said she and her director of photography Lucas Alvarado-Farraire &quot;just wanted to document&quot; the events.
Ferrell came up with a question: &quot;Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play on?&quot;
This skepticism was inspired by the many people, often whites, who came to the community to capitalize on its pain and resilience.
As Folajan explained in a recent interview, “We heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson were not getting into the spotlight and wanted to do it differently.”
Folajan had already teamed up with her co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on death row issues.
His involvement sparked sympathy for the project among Ferrell and six other local residents, with whom the Whose Streets? kept in touch during the years after Brown&#39;s assassination.
“In this documentary, it is not someone who speaks for us or with us, it is we who speak,” Davis said.
&quot;It was the most important for me how these people will be presented, because this is how I myself will be presented.&quot;
And while the project&#39;s goal was not to focus on Ferrell&#39;s experience at all - in an effort to show that the movement “is not about a savior leader, but about how the community is brought together,” as Folajan said - she turned out to be the most open of the participants in the film.
As a result, in &quot;Whose Streets?&quot; unexpectedly personal aspects of Ferrell&#39;s life are shown, such as how she fell in love and married her wife.
“I felt naked,” Ferrell said, laughing about the first time she saw the finished product.
&quot;But I understood that when you do this kind of work and humanize blacks, there must be some level of vulnerability.&quot;
In addition, Ferrell&#39;s story again discusses and emphasizes the role of black homosexual women in the broader context of the Black Lives Matters movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement - those who created the #BlackLivesMatter tag on social media after the murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 - identify themselves as homosexuals.
“Black homosexual women in leadership positions support this whole movement,” Ferrell says. - And all because we are constantly fighting on several fronts.
Black homosexual women have to bear all this burden. &quot;
Folaian agreed with this statement, noting that &quot;the movement is, in fact, supported by black women and many homosexual black women.&quot;
However, she insists that “this is not a case of affirmative action,” and that Ferrell was not chosen as a central character in the film due to her distinctiveness.
“She was the person who awakened this energy,” she said.
“On the other hand, it’s not a coincidence that she came to the fore, because when”
You can feel its energy through the screen. &quot;
In the meantime, Ferguson has long lost movie cameras, but complex racial ties remain between the community and the police.
Ferrell will be on probation for another two and a half years for blocking a highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the place, which she calls home, simply: &quot;Mess.&quot;
She still holds onto the line she learned when she took to the streets of Ferguson three full years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We must win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains. &quot;
