The emergence of similarities: the artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning DNA
In the center of the hall in the Friedman Gallery in New York, human faces hang from the ceiling on a wire - white, black and brown, all subtly similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek strokes and hair scraps sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the scraps from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the famous WikiLeaks transmission of confidential diplomatic cables.
The new exhibition, which opened on 2 August, is titled &quot;The Emergence of Similarity&quot;.
It is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transgender woman and famous dissident who was commuted by Barack Obama just three days before the end of his presidency.
By analyzing the DNA obtained from Manning with a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that might be in people with such a genome, Dewey-Harborg has created a profound, if difficult to understand, manifesto about not only the plasticity of DNA data - the different ways of interpreting them and the inherent determinism of these interpretations - but also the concept of identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has openly stated that she considers herself a woman since adolescence, was sentenced in 2013 on 20 counts, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Pictures of her in prison were not available, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie of Manning in a platinum-tinted wig, clearly uncomfortable, sitting behind the wheel of a car; they began to associate her with this photograph.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg completed her 2012 project, Visions of Strangers, with great success.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, isolating DNA from this debris and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she received an email from Paper Magazine.
“They interviewed Chelsea Manning in jail and wanted a portrait to illustrate the article,” Dewey-Hagborg explained in a preview of the new press exhibition.
At the time, Chelsea was not allowed to be visited and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she would like to receive a portrait created from her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her muse in prison became penpals and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book, Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which depicted how in the future the president would mitigate Chelsea&#39;s punishment so that she could visit the exhibition in person.
That Obama did decide to release Manning just days after the book was published came as a pleasant surprise after seven difficult years in a military prison in Kansas.
There is something deep and powerful about the exhibition opening right now, as Donald Trump declares war on people who disclose classified information in the government and devises new ways to foment the Twitter animosity he is intended to mitigate.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the coincidence of all this in time, she said that &quot;nothing happens by accident.&quot;
In a statement by the artist, written on the gallery wall, Manning&#39;s oversized signature below (with a heart instead of a dot above the &quot;i&quot; in her last name) calls for an end to &quot;automatic separation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture.&quot;
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of penciled C, G, and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist expresses it in a scientifically sophisticated way), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how we are all remarkably similar, at least in our biological structure.
“I hope to explain to people that our genome does not define who we are, how open genetic data is for interpretation, and how subjective it is,” said Dewey-Harborg; her 2007 video work &quot;False Memories&quot; is also on display here.
&quot;DNA data can tell us so many different stories, and 30 of those stories are here.&quot;
The last part of the exhibition, which fits in one room, is the aforementioned novel in comics.
It depicts King Kong-style Manning appearing above the US Correctional Barracks with a loudspeaker in hand.
&quot;If they kill your speech, they will win,&quot; it says.
&quot;So never shut up.&quot;
&quot;This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me,&quot; says the artist greeting us from Philadelphia.
&quot;I still get goosebumps when I talk about it.&quot;
Manning has yet to see the exhibit in person - as it has been visionary in the comics - but when she arrives, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacra gathered like crowds of protesters.
This, too, was done on purpose, like everything at the exhibition up to the height (5 &quot;2, Manning&#39;s height), on which genetic haplogroups were drawn in pencil.
&quot;Before, I would have hung them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people,&quot; Dewey-Harborg says of the portraits.
&quot;I wanted them to be like the grassroots movement that formed around Chelsea, the movement that was behind her liberation as well.&quot;
