Startups that will help your company not become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but the polls didn&#39;t work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees didn&#39;t trust the process.
“He was never consistent or objective,” said Errett, who runs San Francisco-based Madison Reed, a 75-person hair care e-commerce company.
Therefore, she turned to third parties for help.
A new kind of HR startups are emerging that are helping companies figure out how their employees are feeling.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they enable companies to do rapid surveys, reach specific teams and demographics, offer employees anonymity and complaint hotlines, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and contact directly to the management.
“Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Glint, a Redwood City startup whose analytics software is used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said that she gained a greater understanding of how her employees think and feel after three years of using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires of specific teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and shows in a visual form which departments have the most complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies are slowly realizing that they need to control the workplace or they will become another Uber who got involved in a scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive environment in which those who complained were punished ...
For startups like Glint, this desire to be in control is an opportunity for a profitable business.
The financial technology portal Let&#39;s Talk Fees estimates that the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $ 118.7 billion by 2020.
The Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid a decline in Uber&#39;s reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber has recently appeared among the clients.
Like Glint, Convercent enables companies to send custom-made employee opinion surveys, collect confidential real-time responses, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous texting hotline that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if a top manager is involved, complaints go directly to the management.
“The Court of Public Opinion has seized control of the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If a company is found to be mistreating employees or behaving unethically, even if inspectors do not intervene, the company can face costly consequences in the form of customer boycotts, employee churn and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees in 500 locations, has used Convercent for over a year to ensure employees are up to date with policies and procedures and to offer an easy way to contact their headquarters.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look up the phone number or email of the head office, file a formal complaint, and hope to be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, head of legal at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that a company uses Convercent, problems that were previously hidden from managers in offices in other cities or states — such as discrimination, harassment, and unfair pay — can be discovered and addressed more quickly.
“I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the employee situation,” said Vitrano, who leads the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
&quot;And we protect our shareholders from employee litigation.&quot;
According to Quinland, companies began to take ethics, values and employee engagement more seriously in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Case Enron.
But it wasn&#39;t until “social media went mainstream,” that companies realized they couldn&#39;t keep their dirty laundry from going viral online.
“Before using technology to monitor ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee to use their products.
This is a business model and opportunity that has been endorsed by venture capitalists who have backed both startups.
In February, Convercent received $ 10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company&#39;s total capital to $ 47 million.
Glint received $ 10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company&#39;s total capital to $ 60 million.
This investment is hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture, and venture capital.
A growing body of research demonstrates that today&#39;s employees expect more from their jobs than they once did.
In fiercely competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high wages and exciting projects are just the bare minimum.
Employees want to feel accepted and appreciated, and that they are dedicating their time to the company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work for a company, they feel heard, and the work they’re doing is delivering results, they are more committed to making the company successful,” says Nina McQueen, vice president of Global Benefits and Employee Satisfaction at the company. LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors earn income when their portfolio companies are doing well; Companies do well when employees are committed and involved.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, then it should come as no surprise that they find support.
As culture professionals in the workplace argue, it is important to have data on employee engagement.
But the data is useless until the trustees of the company take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can give the impression that change is coming.
And if change doesn&#39;t come quickly enough, or doesn&#39;t come at all, frustration can develop and employees lose interest.
“If you&#39;re going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you have to be prepared to have 4,000 interviews,” says Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don&#39;t go all the way, the staff will wonder, &#39;Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don&#39;t care, why shouldn&#39;t I care? &quot;
Errett said Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action the same day someone reports a problem via Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees who were dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its people and hopes that in the long term, this knowledge will help it better retain employees in an industry known for high turnover.
“If you don’t try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
