Facebook Steps Up Fact Checking Against Fake News
Facebook will more often send texts suspicious of hoaxes to independent experts and show their conclusions under the original posts, the world&#39;s largest social network, which is trying to combat so-called fake news, said on Thursday.
In a statement on its website, the company said it is starting to use improved machine learning algorithms to recognize possible hoaxes, submit them for review, and possibly show the results of fact-checking under the original post.
Facebook has been criticized as one of the main avenues for spreading so-called fake news, which many believe influenced the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
The issue is also being actively debated in Europe after French voters were misled by false messages ahead of the presidential elections in May, and in Germany, ahead of the September elections, announced support for a plan to fine social networks if they did not promptly remove posts that incite hatred.
On Thursday, in a separate statement in German, Facebook announced testing of a new fact-checking algorithm that has been launched in the US, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
“In addition, to see which posts are challenged by independent reviewers, people want to have a broader context to make informed judgments about what they read and what they share,” wrote Sarah Sue, Facebook News Feed Manager.
