Create a Comic Novel: One Castle in English History
In the recent past, tiny Scotney Castle was featured in the music video &quot;Squeeze&quot;, and served as a haven for Margaret Thatcher in the 70s and 80s.
But for 700 years from his cozy spot in the Bule River Valley in Kent, he watched the turbulent history around him, and now he inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire man with a shock of hair and a penchant for historical documents, into a comic book novel.
“I think it&#39;s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a person who died 300 years ago,” he says enthusiastically.
&quot;You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand.&quot;
&quot;Castle in England&quot; covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Evardian era and tells the story of the families who lived in Scotney; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabelle Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes&#39; first book to be based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote Dead Man&#39;s Teeth and Other Stories, a compilation of British Library documents; this project unexpectedly touched him to the core.
“I could just be moved by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites,” he says.
&quot;This is his fingerprint&quot;
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days they lit a fire for lighting.
And after 300 years, in the future, it seems to you that you are there too.
Oh, how I love archives! &quot;
For a man with such a passion for old papers, getting support from the National Trust and the English Arts Council and living in the castle for four months (&quot;Honestly, I stayed a little over there&quot;) seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent whole days exploring the &quot;new&quot; Victorian castle, going through the archives and looking at the estate&#39;s many treasures and antiques - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that had lain in the moat for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking with foresters, gardeners and sometimes with artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he &quot;drank whiskey and sat down to write.&quot;
The history of Scotney Castle is not well understood because the National Trust only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, employees were just starting to deal with the archive, which he describes as &quot;what aristocrats have dumped in the attic for centuries.&quot;
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: “You think land disputes are boring,” says Rhodes, “but this birch tree was fought by two families.
It also happens, guys! &quot;
In some of the stories in the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for broader explorations of English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
&quot;There is evidence of a riot that took place at the castle in 1380 in a book called The Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex,&quot; Rhodes says.
“A peasant uprising started in these places, and I thought the riot was a good start.
Maybe they were related? &quot;
Other plots are strongly associated with the history of the castle - for example, &quot;The Priest&quot;, which tells about the Jesuit priest, whom the Darrel family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, about the 18th century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stoning the coffin (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrels are Rhodes&#39; favorite family of all Scotney&#39;s inhabited: “Gentlemen seem to have been complete crooks, always getting into debt and spending money on what they could not afford.
Over the generations, Darrell men have dealt with their debt problems by marrying rich older women - I think of them as a bunch of nice guys who know how to look after the heirs of great fortunes. &quot;
After graduating from Castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elamänmäki, a place where a sanatorium was at the beginning of the 20th century, and then it was again overgrown with forest.
But Scotney remains a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he says.
&quot;I felt like, damn it, I have to go back to real life again.&quot;
