Andrey Okhlopkov was transferred from the cosmodrome
As it became known to Kommersant, the technical director of the Vostochny cosmodrome, Andrei Okhlopkov, has begun work at the Khrunichev State Space Research and Production Center (GKNPTs).
Previously, he was de facto involved in the construction of the Vostochny cosmodrome, but due to disagreements with the leadership of the Center for the Operation of Ground and Space Infrastructure (TSENKI), he was transferred to an enterprise in Moscow Fili, where he will coordinate production.
Mr. Okhlopkov will not have a replacement: the post of technical director will most likely be abolished, and the functionality will be scattered among the departments of TsENKI.
The fact that the technical director of Vostochny and the deputy general director of TsENKI for technological development Andrey Okhlopkov went to work at the Khrunichev State Research and Production Center, Kommersant was told by top managers of several enterprises in the space industry, as well as an employee of the government apparatus.
&quot;He has been working in his new post for several weeks,&quot; said Kommersant&#39;s interlocutors in the industry.
On Thursday, TsENKI did not manage to get an operative comment, and Mr. Okhlopkov himself was not available for comment.
However, the information of &quot;Kommersant&quot; was officially confirmed by the State Research and Production Space Center.
He made the decision to move to the position of director for production coordination, the company said. - Andrey Okhlopkov fully fulfilled the task assigned to him to ensure the launch minimum for the first launch at the Vostochny cosmodrome.
Mr. Okhlopkov joined TsENKI in 2013, having served in the space forces, in particular at Baikonur, and in Plesetsk - at the &quot;northern&quot; cosmodrome, he held the post of first deputy commander with the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrei Okhlopkov became a defendant in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly with his submission, regional merchants received government orders for kickbacks, but did not fulfill their obligations to clean up detachable parts of launch vehicles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Komi Republic.
In 2012, a jury found him not guilty.
The technological development responsibilities assigned to him at TsENKI extended to various projects, but the main one was the construction of a cosmodrome in the Far East.
Oleg Ostapenko, then head of the Federal Space Agency, said in an interview with Kommersant that the state of affairs on Vostochny &quot;was already critical in October 2013.&quot;
The fact is that a strategic mistake was made in the planning: the completion of construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were scheduled for the same time - the end of 2015.
In order to start up by the end of the year, it was decided to complete the construction six months earlier and the dates were shifted from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, they had to go for a trick: TsENKI specialists began to conduct parallel installation of technological equipment at unfinished facilities.
The main supporter of this idea was Andrey Okhlopkov.
Despite the existing risks and the transfer that happened (instead of December 2015, Soyuz flew away only on April 28, 2016), this idea justified itself, says a Kommersant source at the cosmodrome: one launch from Vostochny, but they would be engaged in construction. &quot;
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the cosmodrome, jokingly called Andrei Okhlopkov his &quot;space Susanin&quot;, but it was he who almost always asked for information on the progress of construction.
I remember Mr. Okhlopkov for his directness: for example, in an interview with Kommersant, he proposed to deprive the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Spetsstroy) of the status of the only executor for Vostochny and work directly with subcontractors: &quot;Why should we put all our eggs in one basket of Spetsstroy?&quot;
This idea found support in the government.
Since 2017, TsENKI has taken over the duties of a general contractor in order to complete construction and installation work at the launch and technical complex by the start-ups planned in the fourth quarter.
According to Kommersant&#39;s information, the reason for the transfer of Mr. Okhlopkov to a new place of work was disagreements with the leadership of TsENKI regarding methods of completing the construction of structures and complexes of the cosmodrome, as well as methods of working with subcontractors.
“It was decided that it would be better for everyone,” says one of the top managers involved in the construction of Vostochny.
An employee of the government apparatus, in turn, calls the decision strange: &quot;He was one of the best specialists, it will not be easy to find an equivalent replacement for him.&quot;
According to Kommersant&#39;s information, this will not be required: the position of the technical director of the cosmodrome will be abolished, and its functions will be scattered across the divisions of TsENKI.
