Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help relieve IBD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests otherwise: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products may help relieve symptoms in those with inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of the protein, tryptophan, promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the intestines make sure that harmful microbes from food do not enter the body.
Cells that can trigger inflammation are balanced with cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed towards inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that tolerance-increasing cells appear in mice with a specific bacterium in their intestines.
And this bacteria needs tryptophan - one of the building blocks of protein - to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have established a link between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had. &quot;
He theorized that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could promote a more tolerant and less inflammatory bowel environment.
Postdoc Dr.Luisa Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying a variety of tolerance-enhancing immune cells, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, while another group, which belonged to the same lineage, but was kept separately, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice - the communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA from the intestinal cells of the mice was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found, present in mice with immune cells, but absent in mice without them.
Mice raised in a sterile environment, which did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells, received L. reuteri, and they developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of the liquid - without bacteria - to underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have turned into tolerance-enhancing cells.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan processing known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the food of the mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells also dropped in half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragán explains that humans have the same tolerance-increasing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known if tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri promote cell development in humans as they do in mice, but defects in genes associated with tryptophan have been found in humans with inflammatory bowel disease.
She says: “Perhaps we need to enhance the development of these cells, since inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High tryptophan levels in the presence of L. reuteri have the potential to expand their population. &quot;
