Props for the White House cost thousands of dollars to taxpayers
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House&#39;s decision last month to bring a Marine Corps helicopter to the South Lawn for an American industrial production event cost taxpayers a whopping $ 24,000.
The green and white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as &quot;Marine One&quot; when the president is on board, became the centerpiece of a July 17 White House event that showcased US construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials inspected technology products from all fifty states.
The Connecticut-built helicopter was displayed alongside a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck and a Mississippi forklift.
According to the records of the 1st Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the department responsible for helicopter control, the White House War Office ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or &quot;FRAGO,&quot; just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn. on the occasion of the &quot;unusual&quot; event.
“I just wanted you to make sure you are in the know because this is an unusual high-profile event,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Marine Corps First Deputy Chief of Air, ahead of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 for the 3 p.m. event and will remain there until the lawn is vacated between 6 and 9 p.m. the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the restrictions on opening hours.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, while the unit&#39;s security personnel remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It is unclear from TIME&#39;s logs whether a second crew was ultimately required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political gain.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event was in conflict with this ruling.
“Among other things, we asked if this was a violation of the Hatch Act, and we were told no,” the commander wrote.
“It looks like you have nowhere to go,” the deputy chief replied.
The Made in America event was declared an official event by the White House and was not subject to Hatch&#39;s law.
But even official events have political overtones.
During the event, the president made efforts to promote health care reform, which was under development in the Senate at the time, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The political use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One is hardly new.
Presidents are instructed to use them for travel.
But asking for them solely in the interests of photographic capability is unusual.
Trump was already a topic of discussion in February, when the presidential plane passed in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was inundated with messages complaining about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
&quot;The White House is thrilled to see Made in America, which showcased 50-state products made by American workers from American materials,&quot; said White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews frequently fly training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and the South Lawn to practice transporting the President of the United States to the White House with an inch of precision.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings outside the White House.
The flight made for the Made in America event was credited to the crew against the required training flights for the month, one official said.
The unit&#39;s helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of &quot;non-presidential support missions.&quot;
According to the White House, taxpayers did not bear the cost of any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in organizing the helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn.
The HMX-1 does not keep track of the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to FY 2017 DOD hourly rates, the DOD reimbursement rate for VH-3D is $ 24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records that the time of the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes in each direction from its airfield at the Quantico Marine Corps Air Base in Virginia.
The White House argues that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than this rate.
